<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Mexican Existentialism</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Sat Mar 29, 2025</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
Mexican existentialism grows out of the encounter, engagement, and
appropriation with French and German existentialist philosophies in
Mexico mid-way through the twentieth-century. Key players in this
tradition were Jos&eacute; Gaos (1900&ndash;1969), Antonio Caso
(1883&ndash;1946), and, especially, <em>el grupo Hiperi&oacute;n</em>
(the Hyperion Group). Members of Hyperion, but particularly Emilio
Uranga (1921&ndash;1988), Leopoldo Zea (1912&ndash;2004), Jorge
Portilla (1918&ndash;1963), and Luis Villoro (1922&ndash;2014),
focused their efforts on existential reinterpretations of <em>that
which is Mexican</em> (&ldquo;lo mexicano&rdquo; or Mexicanness), a
focus that lends this tradition its historical and conceptual
uniqueness and importance.</p>
</div> 

<div id="toc"><!--Entry Contents-->
<ul>
	<li><a href="#BriHisBac">1. Brief Historical Background</a></li>
	<li><a href="#ConInvMexExi">2. Conceptual Inventory of Mexican Existentialism</a>
	<ul>
		<li><a href="#FreCirRes">2.1 Freedom, Circumstance, and Responsibility</a></li>
		<li><a href="#Acc">2.2 Accidentality</a></li>
		<li><a href="#Nep">2.3 Nepantla </a></li>
